---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'adr';
const description =
  'Architecture Decision Records with a real "Considered alternatives" section and a "Reconsider if" trigger. Stops the agent from re-suggesting paths the team already rejected.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    An Architecture Decision Record captures the why behind a choice so future
    agents and humans do not have to re-derive it. With Groundwork, every ADR
    includes a real <em>considered alternatives</em> section (the negative
    space) and a <em>reconsider if</em> trigger that keeps it from becoming a
    tombstone.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    The most subtle form of context debt is <strong>intent debt</strong>: the
    code works, the tests pass, but nobody knows why this particular shape was
    chosen. The next agent suggests GraphQL again. Or Redux. Or whatever you
    rejected six months ago, because the rejection never made it into the
    repo and the agent's training data is full of the alternatives.
  </p>
  <p>
    An ADR is the externalized intent that prevents that. The format is
    MADR-lite: numbered, dated, with status, context, decision, alternatives,
    consequences. Two ingredients are non-negotiable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Considered alternatives.</strong> Real options the team weighed,
      not strawmen. This is the negative space, the most valuable part of the
      file.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reconsider if.</strong> The future-trigger that makes the ADR a
      living artifact rather than a tombstone. When the named condition is
      met, the team knows to revisit.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      ADRs operationalise
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>cognitive debt repayment</a>
      practice #2: externalize intent. Their structure comes from the
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>good practices</a> doc
      (negative space documentation). The
      <a href={url('blueprint/#cognitive-debt')}>2026 Blueprint</a> argues this
      is now board-level.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>A non-obvious technical choice was made.</li>
    <li>An obvious choice was made for a non-obvious reason.</li>
    <li>
      A <em>non-choice</em> was made deliberately. ("We considered GraphQL and
      stayed with REST because…")
    </li>
    <li>A constraint was discovered that will shape future decisions.</li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> flagged a recent
      merge as decision-shaped but ADR-less.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>And when <em>not</em> to write one:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Implementation details the code expresses well on its own.</li>
    <li>
      Preferences with no real tradeoff (indent style goes in conventions, not
      ADRs).
    </li>
    <li>Decisions still being debated. Wait until it is decided.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>One file:</p>
  <pre><code>docs/decisions/&lt;NNNN&gt;-&lt;slug&gt;.md</code></pre>
  <p>
    Plus, if missing, a <code>docs/decisions/README.md</code> and a
    <code>docs/decisions/negative-space.md</code> for lightweight rejections
    that do not warrant a full ADR.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>Three input modes. The command detects which from your first message.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Mode A, live decision.</strong> You describe a choice you are
      making now. The command asks for the four things it needs and drafts.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mode B, from a merged PR.</strong> Paste a PR URL or number.
      The command uses <code>gh pr view</code> (or WebFetch) to pull title,
      description, files, reviews, and dates. It pre-fills almost everything
      and asks only about alternatives and "Reconsider if".
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mode C, from a commit range.</strong> Name commits or an area
      ("last week's auth refactor"). The command reads <code>git log</code>
      and <code>git diff</code>, pre-fills, and surfaces lower-confidence
      inferences for you to correct.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>From there, the procedure is the same:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Find the next number.</strong> Globs existing ADRs, takes the
      max, adds one.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Draft.</strong> Hard rules: context has constraints (not
      background); alternatives has at least one rejected option; reconsider-if
      is specific; title describes the <em>decision</em>, not the topic.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Show the draft.</strong> ADRs are durable. A rushed ADR is
      worse than a delayed ADR.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Set status and write.</strong> <em>accepted</em> if in effect,
      <em>proposed</em> if still being formalized, <em>superseded by
      ADR-NNNN</em> if it replaces an older one (with the older one updated
      too).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cross-link.</strong> If the ADR creates an ongoing rule, a
      one-liner is added to <code>AGENTS.md</code> (or a
      <code>.claude/rules/</code> file if the rule is per-area) pointing back
      at the ADR. The agent reads the rule in the Project layer and can drill
      down for the why.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Negative-space sweep.</strong> Briefly considered options that
      do not deserve a full ADR get a paragraph in
      <code>docs/decisions/negative-space.md</code>. They do not deserve a
      monument; they should not be invisible either.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      Real alternatives, not strawmen. Reconsider-if is named and specific.
      An agent reading the ADR six months later understands the choice without
      further context. Title is the decision, not the topic.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Status: accepted, alternatives: none considered.</strong> The
      most common failure. There were always alternatives. Even "do nothing"
      is one. Surface them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Context paragraph is a brain dump.</strong> Two or three
      paragraphs, focused on the constraints that forced the choice. Trim the
      rest.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No reconsider-if.</strong> Without it, the ADR is a tombstone.
      Always name the future trigger.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Title is the topic.</strong> "Testing framework" is a topic.
      "Use Vitest for unit tests" is a decision. The latter is what searches
      will find.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>Cognitive debt</a>. Intent
      debt and how ADRs repay it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>Good practices</a>. Negative
      space documentation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>Anti-patterns</a> #9: negative
      space silence.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/plan/')}><code>plan</code></a>. Plans often
      surface ADR-worthy decisions; <code>plan</code> step 8 prompts for them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#cognitive-debt')}>2026 Blueprint: externalising intent</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="adr" />
</Doc>
